			<tr>
				<td colspan="2">
					
					


<font face="verdana" size="2"><p><b>Compatible races:</b></font><br>


<font face="verdana" size="1">
<a href='classes.asp?CID=24&mode=details&type=classes'>Dark Elf</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=26&mode=details&type=classes'>Erudite</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=27&mode=details&type=classes'>Gnome</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=30&mode=details&type=classes'>High Elf</a>, <a href='classes.asp?CID=31&mode=details&type=classes'>Human</a>
<font face="verdana" size="3"><p><b>Guide:</b></font><br><br>
<font face="verdana" size="2">
<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>What Race to choose</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">I started out with an Erudite Wizard,&nbsp; which gave me
the maximum amount of <a href="http://www.everlore.com/default.asp?mode=20&amp;id=40">intelligence</a>
you can get.&nbsp; The only thing I can say is that as you increase in level the most
important thing to a wizard is the amount of mana he or she has.&nbsp; I definitely don't
think that Erudites are the best,&nbsp; it is just what I chose.&nbsp; All classes and
race combinations seem to be pretty well balanced.&nbsp; So choose what you like.&nbsp; </font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Starting out: Levels 1-3</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">First thing is to memorize your spells.&nbsp; You can
accomplish this by placing your scrolls in the spells slots on the spell screen.&nbsp; For
a detailed explanation read the EverQuest Manual.&nbsp; After that you want to practice at
the local wizards guild.&nbsp; The guild locations vary so I wont go into that.&nbsp; Than
spend one skill practice point in&nbsp; <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&amp;id=568">Fishing</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&amp;id=588">Piercing</a> to give
them a jump start.&nbsp; This is recommended but no completely necessary.&nbsp; You can
gain skill without putting any practice points in them.&nbsp; Key thing to remember is to
not use all of your practice points.&nbsp; What you want to do is save them for later.
&nbsp; More on that below.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">After the guild you are ready to fight 1 level beasties.
&nbsp; This is were the fun begins.&nbsp; You can, if you wish practice your two spells <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=87&amp;mode=details&amp;spname=Shock+of+Frost">shock
of frost</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=72&amp;mode=details&amp;spname=Minor+Shielding">minor
shielding</a> before you start fighting, but this is not completely necessary.&nbsp; What
I mean by practicing is,&nbsp; target yourself by clicking on, or around your blue heath
meter on the top right of your play screen, and then cast <a
href="www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=87&amp;mode=details&amp;spname=Shock+of+Frost">shock
of frost</a>.&nbsp; What this will accomplish is you will start to raise your <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&amp;id=566">Evocation</a> skill
without paying for it.&nbsp; Same for <a
href="www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=72&amp;mode=details&amp;spname=Minor+Shielding">Minor
Shielding</a>. This way you save your practice points and you better prepare yourself for
the future first level combat.&nbsp; I didn't do this because if you die you just get
placed right back in the newbie zone anyway,&nbsp; and the skills <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&amp;id=566">Evocation</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/skills/default.asp?mode=5&amp;id=537">Abjuration</a> raise
very quickly.&nbsp; Ok, now head to the first zone outside your starting point and start
hacking those snakes or whatever out there.&nbsp; Remember,&nbsp; don't attack anything
that is not White to you.&nbsp; What that means is, when you target a creature by clicking
on it and press the &quot;C&quot; key,&nbsp; the message, in your message viewer displays
in white that this creatures is even to you in level.&nbsp; Any creature that is yellow or
red is higher level than you and should be avoided, any creature blue or green is lower
level than you.&nbsp; Blues and whites are what you want to focus on through to level 4.
&nbsp; At this time don't worry about food and water,&nbsp; because you get it back when
you die,&nbsp; all you need to worry about is raising your skills and getting to level 4.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Ahh!!: Level 4-7</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Ok what spells can I get NOW!&nbsp; Yes you get some, you
worthless wizard.&nbsp; You get <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=177&amp;mode=details&amp;spname=Shock+of+Fire">Shock
of Fire</a> and <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/magic/Magic.asp?ID=156&amp;mode=details&amp;spname=Root">Root</a>!
You want to by Root first and Shock of Fire Second.&nbsp; You really want them both but if
I had to choose it would be root.&nbsp; Now you want to practice this spell until you max.
&nbsp; Once you max your skill go out and start to lump up beasties from afar.&nbsp; Cast
root and then light them up, that's it!&nbsp; Once they free themselves they will becoming
after you so be prepared with your <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/items/items.asp?mode=details&amp;id=630&amp;type=weapon">dagger</a>
or <a
href="http://www.everlore.com/items/items.asp?mode=details&amp;id=626&amp;type=weapon">staff</a>.
&nbsp; By the way if you are lucky enough to have a staff at this point it is the
preferred weapon of a Wizard.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Also now is a good time to find a friend that is the same
level as you.&nbsp; Fighter type classes, wizards, and magicians are good for a twosome.
&nbsp; Fighters of course are a great way to raise levels because he will be keeping that
creature off of you.&nbsp; Same goes for Magicians and there little pets.&nbsp; I prefer
parting with other wizards though!</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><em>Good things about partying with another Wizard</em>:
This is because when you are fighting a creature you need the creature to be away from
you.&nbsp; You cast root then fire away,&nbsp; the creature than gets released and is on
top of you.&nbsp; Now your partner if he is a wizard can cast root on it.&nbsp; Once
rooted for a second time you both can start blasting away.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Levels 8 - 11:</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Well I'm only level 10, so basically what I can tell you
is Buy Shock of Ice, its a must have!&nbsp; This does about 36 hits of damage against most
creatures.&nbsp; Also,&nbsp; the root and shoot tactics still are your bread and butter if
you are soloing.&nbsp; Most of the time you need another party member or you will be
dieing alot or fighting lots of low level creatures.</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">&nbsp;</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2"><strong>Misc.:</strong></font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">I have played a monk a magician and now a wizard and I'm
still undecided on whether a Magician or a Wizard is the one for me.&nbsp; For now I'm
sticking with a wizard.&nbsp; Everyone's different so play what you like.&nbsp; </font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Happy Hunting</font></p>

<p><font face="Verdana" size="2">Eldwin</font></p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

<p>&nbsp;</p>

					
					</p></font>
				</td>
			</tr>
